Why would a country protect their own firm from exposure to world wide markets even though the country engages in international trade? There are a few reasons why a country might protect its own firm from exposure to world wide markets, even though the country engages in international trade. One reason might be to help the country's firms become more competitive in global markets. Another reason might be to help the country's firms protect their intellectual property or other sensitive information. Finally, a country might protect its firms in order to ensure that the country's firms are not harmed by unfair trade practices by other countries.

Why would a country protect their own firm from engaging with markets even though the country itself engages in international trade? There are a few reasons why a country might protect its own firm from engaging with markets. One reason is that the country might want to ensure that its own firms are able to compete in the global marketplace. Another reason is that the country might want to protect its domestic industries from foreign competition.

What would cause a country to prevent its firms from trading internationally? There can be a number of reasons why a country might prevent its firms from trading internationally. One reason might be to protect its domestic industries from foreign competition. Another reason might be to prevent its firms from transferring valuable technology or intellectual property to foreign firms. A third reason might be to prevent its firms from being taken over by foreign firms.

If international trade benefits both countries, why would either country stop any of their firms from trading? There are a number of reasons why a country might stop firms from trading. What does it mean if the cost of free trade is concentrated, but the benefits are dispersed? The cost of free trade is concentrated if it means that some people or companies lose out because they can no longer sell their products in other countries as cheaply as before. The benefits of free trade are dispersed if it means that people or companies can buy cheaper products from other countries.

Do international conflicts prevent trade between two countries that already engage in trade? No, international conflicts do not prevent trade between two countries that already engage in trade. However, international conflicts may lead to a decrease in trade between two countries.

Do certain regime types prevent their firms from trading with other countries? There is no definitive answer to this question as it depends on the specific regime type in question. However, some regimes may restrict or prohibit their firms from trading with certain other countries.
Why are benefits from free trade dispersed? The benefits from free trade are dispersed because they are spread out among all the people in the country who buy and sell goods and services.
